esiastical and secular scholarship. Seventh-century Northumbria was ruled for over 50 years by Gaelic-speaking kings who could access Gaelic traditions. Gaelic literary traditions provide the closest analogues for Bede’s description of Cædmon’s production of Old English poetry. This ground-breaking study displays the transformations created by the growth of vernacular literatures and bilingual intellectual cultures. Gaelic missionaries and educational opportunities helped shape the Northumbrian “Golden Age”, its manuscripts, hagiography, and writings of Aldhelm and Bede.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aScottish Gaelic poetryxHistory and criticism. 4aAltenglisch. 4aMittelalter. 4aMundart. 4aPoesie. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aFili.  aInsular.  aPoetry.  aScop.  aVernacular.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2022 Part 1z97831107668200 cEPUBz97815015139300 cprintz978150152028040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150151387940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501513879423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501513879/original  a978-3-11-076682-0  DG Plus DeG Package 2022 Part 1b2022  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK